======================================================================
PART 1: THE K-NACCI CONSTANTS
======================================================================

The k-nacci sequence generalizes Fibonacci:
  k=2: Fibonacci     a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2)         ratio → φ ≈ 1.618
  k=3: Tribonacci    a(n) = a(n-1) + a(n-2) + a(n-3) ratio → τ ≈ 1.839
  k=4: Tetranacci    a(n) = Σ a(n-i) for i=1..4      ratio → ≈ 1.928
  k→∞:                                                ratio → 2

  k=  2: ratio = 1.6180339887  (2 - ratio = 0.3819660113)
  k=  3: ratio = 1.8392867552  (2 - ratio = 0.1607132448)
  k=  4: ratio = 1.9275619755  (2 - ratio = 0.0724380245)
  k=  5: ratio = 1.9659482366  (2 - ratio = 0.0340517634)
  k=  6: ratio = 1.9835828434  (2 - ratio = 0.0164171566)
  k=  7: ratio = 1.9919641966  (2 - ratio = 0.0080358034)
  k=  8: ratio = 1.9960311797  (2 - ratio = 0.0039688203)
  k= 10: ratio = 1.9990186327  (2 - ratio = 0.0009813673)
  k= 20: ratio = 1.9999990463  (2 - ratio = 0.0000009537)
  k= 50: ratio = 2.0000000000  (2 - ratio = 0.0000000000)

  As k→∞, ratio → 2 (the k-nacci constant approaches 2)
  The TOURNAMENT GENERATOR 2 is the LIMIT of k-nacci ratios!

======================================================================
PART 2: WEIGHTED K-NACCI → 3
======================================================================

Weighted k-nacci at x=2: a(n) = 2·a(n-1) + 2·a(n-2) + ... + 2·a(n-k)
  This is the k-nacci with each term weighted by x=2.
  Equivalently: char poly = x^k - 2(x^{k-1} + ... + 1) = x^k - 2(x^k-1)/(x-1)

  The dominant root approaches 2k/(k-1)... let's compute:

  k=  2: weighted ratio = 2.7320508076  (3 - ratio = 0.2679491924)
  k=  3: weighted ratio = 2.9196395658  (3 - ratio = 0.0803604342)
  k=  4: weighted ratio = 2.9744492446  (3 - ratio = 0.0255507554)
  k=  5: weighted ratio = 2.9916541014  (3 - ratio = 0.0083458986)
  k=  6: weighted ratio = 2.9972413302  (3 - ratio = 0.0027586698)
  k=  7: weighted ratio = 2.9990835473  (3 - ratio = 0.0009164527)
  k=  8: weighted ratio = 2.9996949203  (3 - ratio = 0.0003050797)
  k= 10: weighted ratio = 2.9999661260  (3 - ratio = 0.0000338740)
  k= 20: weighted ratio = 2.9999999994  (3 - ratio = 0.0000000006)

  As k→∞, weighted ratio → 3 = 1+x = simplex factor!
  The SIMPLEX GENERATOR (x+1)=3 is the limit of weighted k-nacci!

  INTERPRETATION:
    k-nacci → 2 = cuboid factor (x+2)/2 ... no.
    Actually: k-nacci → 2 = number of arc states per edge
    Weighted k-nacci at x=2 → 3 = simplex volume factor (1+x)
    These are (x+2)^n and (1+x)^n at x=2!

======================================================================
PART 3: THE TRIBONACCI CONSTANT τ
======================================================================

Tribonacci constant τ = 1.839286755214161
  Real root of x³ - x² - x - 1 = 0
  Equivalently: x³ = x² + x + 1 = Φ₃(x)!

  *** τ³ = Φ₃(τ) = τ² + τ + 1 ***
  Verify: τ³ = 6.2222625231
          τ²+τ+1 = 6.2222625231

  THE TRIBONACCI CONSTANT SATISFIES τ³ = Φ₃(τ)!
  This is the DEFINING RELATIONSHIP connecting tribonacci to Φ₃!

  Rewriting: x³ - (x²+x+1) = 0  →  x³ = Φ₃(x)

  Compare with golden ratio: φ² = φ + 1 = Φ₂(φ)? 
    φ = 1.6180339887
    φ² = 2.6180339887
    φ+1 = 2.6180339887
    Φ₂(φ) = φ+1 = 2.6180339887

  Actually φ² = φ+1, and x²-x-1 = 0 means x² = x+1.
  For Fibonacci: x² = x + 1 (sum of 2 terms)
  For tribonacci: x³ = x² + x + 1 = Φ₃(x) (sum of 3 terms)
  For k-nacci:    x^k = x^{k-1} + ... + x + 1 = (x^k-1)/(x-1)

  THE K-NACCI EQUATION: x^k = (x^k - 1)/(x - 1)
  Rearranging: x^k(x-1) = x^k - 1
               x^{k+1} - x^k = x^k - 1
               x^{k+1} = 2x^k - 1

  At the limit k→∞: if x = 2-ε, then
  (2-ε)^{k+1} ≈ 2(2-ε)^k - 1
  This gives x → 2 as k → ∞ ✓

  τ = 1.8392867552
  τ² = 3.3829757679
  τ³ = 6.2222625231 = Φ₃(τ)
  Φ₃(τ) = τ²+τ+1 = 6.2222625231
  Φ₃(2) = 7
  Φ₃(φ) = φ²+φ+1 = 5.2360679775
         = (φ+1)+φ+1 = 2φ+2 = 5.2360679775
         = 2+√5 = 4.2360679775

  Φ₃(φ) = 2+√5 ≈ 4.236068
  Φ₃(τ) = τ³ ≈ 6.222263
  Φ₃(2) = 7 (integer!)
  Φ₃(3) = 13 (integer!)

