======================================================================
PART 5: BASE-τ AND Φ₃
======================================================================

Since τ³ = Φ₃(τ) = τ²+τ+1, base-τ has special properties:

  In base τ:
    τ = 10                (by definition)
    τ² = 100
    τ³ = 1000 = 111       (because τ³ = τ²+τ+1)
    This means: 1000 = 111 in base τ!
    The tribonacci 'carrying rule': three consecutive 1s = one 1 three places left

  Verification:
    τ² + τ + 1 = 3.382976 + 1.839287 + 1 = 6.222263
    τ³ = 6.222263
    Match: True

  Compare with base φ:
    φ² = φ+1, so in base φ: 100 = 11
    The Fibonacci carrying rule: two consecutive 1s = one 1 two places left

  Compare with base 2:
    2² = 2+2, so in base 2: 100 = ... (normal binary)
    No carrying rule involving sums of lower digits

  THE CARRYING RULES ARE THE K-NACCI RECURRENCES!
  base φ: 100_φ = 11_φ      → Fibonacci carrying (2 terms)
  base τ: 1000_τ = 111_τ    → Tribonacci carrying (3 terms)
  base k-nacci: 10...0 = 1...1  → k-nacci carrying (k terms)

======================================================================
PART 6: Φ₃ IN BASE τ vs BASE φ vs BASE 2
======================================================================

Evaluating Φ₃(x) = x²+x+1 at different bases:

  Φ₃(τ) = τ³ = 6.2222625231
    In base τ: 1000
    Or equivalently: 111 (using tribonacci carrying)
    The Fano-like value in base τ is just 'three ones'!

  Φ₃(φ) = 2+√5 = 4.2360679775
    = φ² + φ + 1 = (φ+1) + φ + 1 = 2φ+2
    In base φ: 100 + 10 + 1 = 111_φ
    But 111_φ = φ²+φ+1 is NOT the same as writing 111 in base φ
    (In Zeckendorf, 111 is not allowed since φ²=φ+1 means 100=11)

  Φ₃(2) = 7
    In base 2: 111
    7 = 4+2+1 = 2²+2¹+2⁰ = 111₂

  Φ₃(3) = 13
    In base 3: 111
    13 = 9+3+1 = 3²+3¹+3⁰ = 111₃

  *** Φ₃(x) = x²+x+1 IS the number 111 in base x! ***

  This is OBVIOUS but PROFOUND:
  The 'Fano number' 7 = 111₂
  The 'PG(2,3) number' 13 = 111₃
  The 'Baer number' 21 = 111₄ (base 4)
  The projective plane PG(2,q) has 111_q points!

  21 in base 4: 21 = 4²+4+1 = 16+4+1 = 21 = 111₄ ✓

  MORE GENERALLY:
  PG(k-1, q) has q^{k-1}+q^{k-2}+...+q+1 = 111...1_q (k ones) points
  This is the number (q^k-1)/(q-1) = 'k ones in base q'

  For k=3 (projective planes):
    PG(2,2) = 111₂ = 7
    PG(2,3) = 111₃ = 13
    PG(2,4) = 111₄ = 21
    PG(2,5) = 111₅ = 31

  For k=2 (projective lines):
    PG(1,2) = 11₂ = 3
    PG(1,3) = 11₃ = 4
    PG(1,4) = 11₄ = 5
    PG(1,5) = 11₅ = 6

  THE FORBIDDEN VALUES ARE 'ALL ONES' NUMBERS:
  7 = 111₂ = repunit in base 2
  21 = 111₄ = repunit in base 4 = base 2²
  273 = 111₁₆ = repunit in base 16 = base 2⁴ (NOT forbidden)

======================================================================
PART 7: SIMPLEX-CUBOID PACKING
======================================================================

User's framework: simplex = (x+1)^n, cuboid = (x+2)^n at x=2
  Simplex volume factor: (1+x)^n = 3^n
  Cuboid volume factor:  (2+x)^n = 4^n

  Packing ratio: simplex/cuboid = (3/4)^n = ((1+x)/(2+x))^n
  This is the fraction of cuboid volume occupied by the simplex.

  Complement = 1 - (3/4)^n = 'extra pieces' fraction
  n=1: (3/4)^1 = 0.750000, complement = 0.250000, extra = 4^1-3^1 = 1
  n=2: (3/4)^2 = 0.562500, complement = 0.437500, extra = 4^2-3^2 = 7
  n=3: (3/4)^3 = 0.421875, complement = 0.578125, extra = 4^3-3^3 = 37
  n=4: (3/4)^4 = 0.316406, complement = 0.683594, extra = 4^4-3^4 = 175
  n=5: (3/4)^5 = 0.237305, complement = 0.762695, extra = 4^5-3^5 = 781
  n=6: (3/4)^6 = 0.177979, complement = 0.822021, extra = 4^6-3^6 = 3367
  n=7: (3/4)^7 = 0.133484, complement = 0.866516, extra = 4^7-3^7 = 14197
  n=8: (3/4)^8 = 0.100113, complement = 0.899887, extra = 4^8-3^8 = 58975

  The extra pieces 4^n - 3^n:
    n=1:      1  mod 7 = 1  
    n=2:      7  mod 7 = 0  = 7·1
    n=3:     37  mod 7 = 2  
    n=4:    175  mod 7 = 0  = 7·25
    n=5:    781  mod 7 = 4  
    n=6:   3367  mod 7 = 0  = 7·481
    n=7:  14197  mod 7 = 1  
    n=8:  58975  mod 7 = 0  = 7·8425

  7 | (4^n - 3^n) iff n is even (since 4≡3≡-1 mod 7 fails...)
  Actually: 4 ≡ 4 mod 7, 3 ≡ 3 mod 7
  4^n - 3^n mod 7:
    n=1: 4^1 ≡ 4, 3^1 ≡ 3, diff ≡ 1 mod 7
    n=2: 4^2 ≡ 2, 3^2 ≡ 2, diff ≡ 0 mod 7
    n=3: 4^3 ≡ 1, 3^3 ≡ 6, diff ≡ 2 mod 7
    n=4: 4^4 ≡ 4, 3^4 ≡ 4, diff ≡ 0 mod 7
    n=5: 4^5 ≡ 2, 3^5 ≡ 5, diff ≡ 4 mod 7
    n=6: 4^6 ≡ 1, 3^6 ≡ 1, diff ≡ 0 mod 7
    n=7: 4^7 ≡ 4, 3^7 ≡ 3, diff ≡ 1 mod 7
    n=8: 4^8 ≡ 2, 3^8 ≡ 2, diff ≡ 0 mod 7
    n=9: 4^9 ≡ 1, 3^9 ≡ 6, diff ≡ 2 mod 7
    n=10: 4^10 ≡ 4, 3^10 ≡ 4, diff ≡ 0 mod 7
    n=11: 4^11 ≡ 2, 3^11 ≡ 5, diff ≡ 4 mod 7
    n=12: 4^12 ≡ 1, 3^12 ≡ 1, diff ≡ 0 mod 7
  Period of (4^n - 3^n) mod 7: 6 = tournament period!

======================================================================
PART 8: SIMPLEX NESTING AND CORNER PIECES
======================================================================

The user's geometric picture:
  n=2: equilateral triangle in square, 2 corner triangles
  n=3: regular tetrahedron in cube, 4 corner pieces

  For a regular n-simplex inscribed in an n-cube:
  A regular simplex with n+1 vertices can inscribe in an n-cube
  when a Hadamard matrix H_{n+1} exists (n+1 ≡ 0 mod 4 or n+1 ≤ 2)

  HADAMARD DIMENSIONS: n+1 = 1, 2, 4, 8, 12, 16, 20, ...
  So n = 0, 1, 3, 7, 11, 15, 19, ...

  At these dimensions, the simplex inscribes perfectly and
  the 'corner pieces' are congruent orthoschemes.

  Volume ratios (simplex/cube) at Hadamard dimensions:
  n=1: vol ratio ≈ 1.000000, corner pieces = 2^1-2 = 0
  n=2: vol ratio ≈ 0.433013, corner pieces = 2^2-3 = 1
  n=3: vol ratio ≈ 0.333333, corner pieces = 2^3-4 = 4
  n=7: vol ratio ≈ 0.025397, corner pieces = 2^7-8 = 120

  THE KEY PATTERN:
  n=1: 2^1 - 2 = 0 pieces (simplex = segment = cube)
  n=2: 2^2 - 3 = 1 piece  (triangle + 1 complement)
  n=3: 2^3 - 4 = 4 pieces (tetrahedron + 4 corners)
  n=7: 2^7 - 8 = 120 = 5! pieces

  General: 2^n - (n+1) = Σ C(n,k) for k≥2 = interaction terms
  These are the higher-order terms in (1+1)^n = 2^n
  The simplex captures the 'linear' part: C(n,0)+C(n,1) = 1+n
  The corners capture the 'nonlinear' part: C(n,2)+C(n,3)+...

  IN TOURNAMENT TERMS:
  The simplex ↔ degree-0 and degree-1 Walsh components = mean + linear
  The corners ↔ degree-2 and higher Walsh components = interactions
  H is determined by degree-2+ interactions (the 'corner pieces'!)

======================================================================
PART 9: THE TRIBONACCI-BAER CONNECTION
======================================================================

Since τ³ = Φ₃(τ) and Φ₃(2) = 7, Φ₃(4) = 21:

  The tribonacci constant satisfies THE SAME polynomial relation
  that generates the forbidden values, just at an irrational point.

  Think of it as a continuous version:
  Φ₃(x) evaluated at integer points gives projective planes
  Φ₃(x) evaluated at k-nacci constants gives k-nacci^(k+1)

  k-nacci ratios and Φ₃ values:
  k= 2: ratio=1.61803399, Φ₃(r) = 5.236068, r^k = 2.618034, r³ = 4.236068
  k= 3: ratio=1.83928676, Φ₃(r) = 6.222263, r^k = 6.222263, r³ = 6.222263
  k= 4: ratio=1.92756198, Φ₃(r) = 6.643057, r^k = 13.804904, r³ = 7.161847
  k= 5: ratio=1.96594824, Φ₃(r) = 6.830901, r^k = 29.367055, r³ = 7.598296
  k= 6: ratio=1.98358284, Φ₃(r) = 6.918184, r^k = 60.911888, r³ = 7.804607
  k=10: ratio=1.99901863, Φ₃(r) = 6.995094, r^k = 1018.986480, r³ = 7.988229

  For k=3 (tribonacci): Φ₃(τ) = τ³ EXACTLY
  For k=2 (Fibonacci): Φ₃(φ) = 2+√5 ≈ 4.236, φ³ ≈ 4.236 — WAIT
    φ³ = 4.2360679775
    Φ₃(φ) = 5.2360679775
    φ³ = Φ₃(φ)? False

  WAIT: φ³ = φ·φ² = φ(φ+1) = φ²+φ = (φ+1)+φ = 2φ+1
    2φ+1 = 4.2360679775
    Φ₃(φ) = φ²+φ+1 = (φ+1)+φ+1 = 2φ+2 = 5.2360679775
    So φ³ = 2φ+1 ≠ 2φ+2 = Φ₃(φ)
    The Fibonacci equation is φ² = φ+1, NOT φ³ = Φ₃(φ)

  THE DISTINCTION:
  Fibonacci: φ² = φ+1  (degree 2 relation)
  Tribonacci: τ³ = τ²+τ+1 = Φ₃(τ)  (degree 3 relation)
  The tribonacci is the UNIQUE constant where x^3 = Φ₃(x)

======================================================================
PART 10: REPUNITS AND TOURNAMENT FORBIDDEN VALUES
======================================================================

REPUNIT: a number consisting of all 1s in some base
  R_k(b) = 111...1_b (k ones) = (b^k - 1)/(b - 1)

  R_3(b) = b² + b + 1 = Φ₃(b)  (3-digit repunit = Φ₃)
  R_2(b) = b + 1               (2-digit repunit)
  R_k(b) = Σ b^i for i=0..k-1   (k-digit repunit)

  FORBIDDEN VALUES AS REPUNITS:
  7 = R_3(2) = 111₂  (base-2 repunit)
  21 = R_3(4) = 111₄ (base-4 repunit)
  273 = R_3(16) = 111₁₆ (base-16 repunit, NOT forbidden)

  These are 3-digit repunits in base 2^{2^k}:
  k=0: R_3(2) = 7 ← FORBIDDEN
  k=1: R_3(4) = 21 ← FORBIDDEN
  k=2: R_3(16) = 273 ← achievable

  OTHER REPUNIT SEQUENCES:
  2-digit repunits R_2(b) = b+1: 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, ...
    R_2(2) = 3 = Φ₆(2), R_2(6) = 7 = Φ₃(2)
    7 is BOTH R_3(2) and R_2(6)!

  4-digit repunits R_4(b) = b³+b²+b+1:
    R_4(2) = 15 = (b+1)(b²+1) = 3×5
    R_4(3) = 40 = (b+1)(b²+1) = 4×10
    R_4(4) = 85 = (b+1)(b²+1) = 5×17
    R_4(5) = 156 = (b+1)(b²+1) = 6×26
    R_4(6) = 259 = (b+1)(b²+1) = 7×37
    R_4(7) = 400 = (b+1)(b²+1) = 8×50

  R_4(b) = (b+1)(b²+1) always factors!
  So 4-digit repunits are NEVER prime.
  But 3-digit repunits R_3(b) = Φ₃(b) can be prime.

  Primality of R_3(b) = Φ₃(b):
    Φ₃( 2) =    7 PRIME
    Φ₃( 3) =   13 PRIME
    Φ₃( 4) =   21  = 3 × 7
    Φ₃( 5) =   31 PRIME
    Φ₃( 6) =   43 PRIME
    Φ₃( 7) =   57  = 3 × 19
    Φ₃( 8) =   73 PRIME
    Φ₃( 9) =   91  = 7 × 13
    Φ₃(10) =  111  = 3 × 37
    Φ₃(11) =  133  = 7 × 19
    Φ₃(12) =  157 PRIME
    Φ₃(13) =  183  = 3 × 61
    Φ₃(14) =  211 PRIME
    Φ₃(15) =  241 PRIME
    Φ₃(16) =  273  = 3 × 7 × 13
    Φ₃(17) =  307 PRIME
    Φ₃(18) =  343  = 7 × 7 × 7
    Φ₃(19) =  381  = 3 × 127

  Φ₃ primes (b such that Φ₃(b) is prime):
  b = 1(3), 2(7), 3(13), 5(31), 6(43), 8(73), 12(157), 14(211), ...
  These are called 'generalized Eisenstein primes' — norms of
  Eisenstein primes in Z[ω].

======================================================================
PART 11: THE CATEGORY OF REPUNITS
======================================================================

Define the REPUNIT FUNCTOR:
  R_k: (Bases) → (Integers)
  b ↦ R_k(b) = (b^k-1)/(b-1)

  Morphisms: b₁ = b₂^m gives R_k(b₂^m) | R_{km}(b₂)
  because 111...1_{b^m} (k digits) embeds into 111...1_b (km digits)

  At k=3: R_3(2) = 7, R_3(4) = 21, R_3(16) = 273
  Divisibility: R_3(2) | R_3(4)? 7 | 21 = 3×7 ✓
  R_3(4) | R_3(16)? 21 | 273 = 13×21 ✓
  R_3(2^{2^k}) divides R_3(2^{2^{k+1}}) for all k!

  The Baer divisibility tower:
    R_3(2) = 7
    R_3(4) = 21 = R_3(2) × 3
    R_3(16) = 273 = R_3(4) × 13
    R_3(256) = 65793 = R_3(16) × 241
    R_3(65536) = 4295032833 = R_3(256) × 65281

  The quotients: 3, 13, 241, 65281, ...
  These are Φ₆(2^{2^k}) = q² - q + 1 at q = 2^{2^k}!
  This IS the Baer partition: each PG(2,F_{q²}) contains
  Φ₆(q) = q²-q+1 copies of PG(2,F_q).

======================================================================
PART 12: SYNTHESIS — THE REPUNIT-TRIBONACCI-BAER TRIANGLE
======================================================================

THREE WINDOWS onto the same structure:

  1. REPUNITS: Φ₃(b) = 111_b = 3-digit repunit in base b
     Forbidden values = repunits in bases 2, 4
     The 'all ones' structure = every position contributes equally

  2. TRIBONACCI: τ³ = Φ₃(τ) = τ²+τ+1
     The tribonacci recurrence IS the Φ₃ polynomial relation
     τ is the 'irrational base' where Φ₃ becomes a pure power

  3. BAER PLANES: |PG(2,q)| = Φ₃(q) = 111_q
     The projective plane IS the repunit geometry
     Each 'digit position' (0, 1, 2) corresponds to a coordinate axis
     The 111 structure means: one point for each combination

  THE UNITY:
  A projective plane PG(2,q) has q²+q+1 = 111_q points.
  This is Φ₃(q), the third cyclotomic polynomial.
  At q = τ (tribonacci), this becomes τ³ = Φ₃(τ).
  At q = 2 (tournament base), this becomes 7 = FORBIDDEN.
  The repunit '111' is the universal form, and the base
  determines which mathematical world we're in.

  FORBIDDEN VALUES = REPUNITS IN TOURNAMENT-RELATED BASES
  The base 2 is the tournament generator (2 states per arc)
  The base 4 = 2² is the Baer square (F₄ field size)
  Together, 7 = 111₂ and 21 = 111₄ are the only forbidden repunits.

======================================================================
DONE — TRIBONACCI BASES BAER
